WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.440
Positive comp, this is cool. Okay, so Annapurna. Annapurna is the 10th tallest mountain in the

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:15.280
world. It was, in 1950, the first 8,000 plus meter peak to be summited by an expedition of

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:20.959
mountaineers led by Werner Herzog. It's this classic tale of, like, disaster in the mountains.

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:27.840
The thing I think a lot about when I think of Annapurna is that after a year of planning

00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:33.680
this expedition, the team got to Nepal. They spent a year getting permits, training. This,

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:38.080
of course, was the culmination of years of training, right, to be elite, elite world-class

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:43.520
mountaineers. They get on the ground in Nepal, and they're not sure how to get to the mountain.

00:00:44.639 --> 00:00:49.040
And, in fact, this is super apt, I think, for thinking about data science. They don't even,

00:00:49.599 --> 00:00:53.360
it's not just that they don't know how to get to the base of Annapurna, they're not sure if

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:58.400
they want to climb Annapurna. They've got their eyes on this other mountain, Dalgiri, that's also

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:03.919
an 8,000 plus meter peak. So, they know that they want to climb one of these two 8,000 meter peaks,

00:01:03.919 --> 00:01:07.440
but they're not sure which one. But they brought all their gear, and they trained,

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:12.160
and they're really ready. So, the first problem is, like, we've got to get to the mountain.

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:18.639
So, I think about this situation a lot when I have conversations with my team that go something like,

00:01:19.599 --> 00:01:24.559
they go something like, it's all around this theme of, like, are we really data scientists?

00:01:24.559 --> 00:01:29.279
So, questions like, when we get to be data scientists, will we be able to,

00:01:29.279 --> 00:01:33.839
and it's use a certain method, it's employ a certain kind of statistical technique,

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:40.879
or can we really be doing data science if we're not, this is when we tend to get into specific

00:01:40.879 --> 00:01:46.320
tools, if we're not using, like, the newest tool, if we're not using a specific method,

00:01:46.559 --> 00:01:50.239
if we're not using a specific application stack, this gets into really specific,

00:01:50.239 --> 00:01:53.360
like, in the weeds of, like, the way that we want to practice our work.

00:01:55.279 --> 00:01:59.760
Or questions like, am I really doing data science if I, like, I spent all this month

00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:05.519
solving infrastructure problems? I spent the whole week figuring out, like, database drivers.

00:02:05.519 --> 00:02:09.600
Like, every time I fire up a project that has to connect to Oracle, I kind of hold my breath,

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:13.360
because I wonder, am I going to spend the week instead solving that database driver problem?

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:19.600
So, I talk about this kind of stuff with my team, and my instinct, I believe in a really

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:24.639
expansive definition of data science that encompasses a lot of different kinds of activities.

00:02:24.639 --> 00:02:28.800
And so, I say, yeah, we're data scientists, because I want to be really encouraging and

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:33.679
really affirming of the work that we're doing. So, in doing this coaching with my team, I say,

00:02:33.679 --> 00:02:37.039
yeah, we're data scientists, and then I throw a bunch of rakes out on the ground, and I, like,

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:40.479
I step on all of them, because I immediately start to qualify it with things like,

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:45.759
even when some of the work may not look like data science, no, that's not the way I want to

00:02:45.759 --> 00:02:52.080
reinforce this message. Or I say, yeah, we're data scientists, although I know you want to do more of

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:59.039
machine learning, or AI stuff, or proc life reg. And that's my one SAS joke that I'm allowed to

00:02:59.039 --> 00:03:04.639
make, because it's where I learned survival analysis. The problem with this conversation,

00:03:05.600 --> 00:03:10.080
the problem with this conversation, and the problem that I step into, even though I don't

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:17.360
want to, is that I think we have this sense in this business that there's a kind of value-laden

00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:26.960
continuum along which data science is the peak to really push that entry point. And there's all

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:31.839
these other kinds of activity that as data scientists, well, maybe we have to do to get

00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:37.440
there, but that doesn't really define the work necessarily. And I think that that becomes a

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:44.479
really harmful cycle of feeling like I'm always not quite doing the valuable work that I want to

00:03:44.479 --> 00:03:48.960
be doing. Or the thing that has the most payoff, the most value for my organization, or the most

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:54.000
value for me personally, from a skill building perspective, is not where I have to spend my time.

00:03:54.960 --> 00:04:02.880
So I spent a lot of time thinking about how do we make an environment where for teams like mine,

00:04:02.880 --> 00:04:08.320
we don't feel like we're constantly getting pushed around on this value continuum of what's the work

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:14.880
that we're doing. So a little bit about my team, and I think this really describes a whole lot of

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:19.600
teams doing this sort of work. Sometimes we get to be strategic. We get to be in conversations

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:25.200
about what's our technical roadmap? What kinds of tools do we want to use in a year? How do we get

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:32.079
there? How do we develop along that path? Really day to day, we do a ton of just ad hoc problem

00:04:32.079 --> 00:04:38.239
solving. We've got to get data to a consumer. Along the way, we've got to transform it in some

00:04:38.239 --> 00:04:42.640
challenging ways. And maybe we have to do that in a slightly different way every week.

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:49.040
This is the kind of situation that my team ends up in a lot because we span a whole bunch of

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:54.959
different functions. So we don't have this continuous pipeline of where we're refining a

00:04:54.959 --> 00:04:59.119
method and refining a method and refining a method. We're solving different problems for

00:04:59.119 --> 00:05:06.720
different projects every month. And that can make it really hard to feel like we're pushing along a

00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:15.119
single continuum of skills. I think this characterizes lots of data teams. And continuing

00:05:15.119 --> 00:05:22.160
in the tradition of hand-drawn sketches having a great deal of quantitative rigor, as long as you

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:28.640
don't interrogate the x-axis too much, I think this really has unimpeachable face validity.

00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:35.200
A lot of data teams, maybe most data teams, are in the space where we can sort of ideate about

00:05:35.200 --> 00:05:41.440
that far end of the spectrum. That's the sort of rarefied air of data science as I think the

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:47.200
industry promotes. And as I think even a lot of our leaders tend to promote when they ask us

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:52.480
things like, why isn't our organization doing more machine learning? Well, you need to bring

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:57.200
us some use cases that demand it, and then we can get into that work. But in the meantime,

00:05:57.200 --> 00:06:02.000
we've got all kinds of problems that we need to solve. And at the same time, we're too big. And

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:07.600
we have too much of an enterprise technology stack to be able to respond in nimble ways to some of

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:14.799
the developments that are really exciting the way that smaller teams can respond. So we work in

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:22.000
this space where the model for the job is often not the way that we can practice the job. And I

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:26.880
think that creates this really, really profound sometimes sense of sort of fear of missing out,

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:32.399
and the sense of kind of a contest culture over who gets to practice with the tools that are the

00:06:32.399 --> 00:06:38.640
really exciting tools in this space. And so I think a bunch about how do we make data science

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:45.600
jobs more healthy for data scientists, for people working in these jobs? And I have a few ways that

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:53.519
over a few years, I think I've had some success. We'll see how it goes. The first one, and this

00:06:53.519 --> 00:06:58.559
applies both to folks who are hiring, to team leaders, and also to folks who are, to data

00:06:58.559 --> 00:07:04.480
scientists, folks who are looking for jobs. Both sides, all of these folks involved need to set

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:09.760
expectations really carefully and really honestly so that we're describing the work that we have in

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:18.799
our teams in an accurate way. So here's some bullet points from job descriptions for roles

00:07:18.799 --> 00:07:24.160
on my teams. And you'll see that there's a progression here. Develop and build data assets

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:31.040
and models. Okay, in the service of like business insights for our stakeholders. This is the sort of

00:07:31.040 --> 00:07:36.959
like data science top line where people go, hey, that sounds good. Building data sets, gathering

00:07:36.959 --> 00:07:45.040
value from data, presenting it to stakeholders. This sounds cool. Become a subject matter expert

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:51.519
for needed processes and data domains. Okay, this still sounds like it's in the realm of things that

00:07:51.600 --> 00:07:56.160
I want to practice, although maybe it's getting a little close into the like

00:07:56.160 --> 00:08:01.119
sort of application side of things or the business process side of things. And that's not

00:08:01.119 --> 00:08:06.720
necessarily what some folks are signing up for. And then there's the end where we have to

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:12.799
solve problems in this space all the time. Build and support capability, work on integrations, work

00:08:12.799 --> 00:08:18.799
on pipelines, work on getting data from place to place so that we can partner with analysts and

00:08:18.799 --> 00:08:25.200
with others to do good work with it. This kind of conversation is a sort of conversation that

00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:33.039
I've had with everyone who wants to come onto my team. And some people say, great, I like

00:08:33.039 --> 00:08:37.599
this array of things. I could really be successful here. Other people say, no, there's too much here

00:08:37.599 --> 00:08:43.679
that I don't want to do. The sooner we can have that conversation and the sooner both sort of

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:48.880
parties can think about it realistically and kind of gut check with themselves honestly, like,

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:56.159
so this is a job I want, the better. Because if you go down the road, having had a mismatch, you get

00:08:56.159 --> 00:09:03.520
into really dangerous territory. The most challenging situation I've been in as a leader

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:11.119
of a team is with a person sort of working peripherally to our team, but in a related space

00:09:11.679 --> 00:09:16.479
for whom this work of kind of aligning expectations of the job with the expectations

00:09:16.479 --> 00:09:21.440
that they had for what the job ought to be, like that work wasn't done successfully enough.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:26.960
And you get several months down the road in a project and you realize that you need

00:09:29.119 --> 00:09:33.359
this person that they're not ready to do or maybe not willing to do.

00:09:34.159 --> 00:09:37.599
And in the meantime, the work is suffering. It creates this really

00:09:38.159 --> 00:09:43.440
almost catastrophic kind of scenario for the rest of the team as well, observing like the breakdown

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:51.760
of effectiveness that the team feels. And so the peak of this conflict that I've experienced

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:56.960
was this almost catastrophic effect on work that we'd been doing for years that can really just

00:09:56.960 --> 00:10:05.599
hit a wall when the folks who you need to help deliver work can't or won't. And that's a failure

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:13.520
of being realistic and honest on both sides. Leaders have got to honestly present what is

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:18.640
the job. And as job seekers, as data scientists, you've got to honestly sort of check in with

00:10:18.640 --> 00:10:27.200
yourself on, can I do the work as is being described here? If not, you've really got to

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:30.880
think it's not going to work and you're going to go down the road and you're going to hit a wall.

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:38.640
So that's the first piece, set expectations really carefully. The second piece is as a leader,

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:43.039
this is where you get to start to be a little bit more active. Once you've got people on your team,

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:49.359
this is where you can start to think about meeting the needs of your business and balancing them

00:10:49.359 --> 00:10:54.320
with the aspirations of the folks on your team. And this is sort of the balance between the what

00:10:54.320 --> 00:10:59.440
and the how. The what of course is like, what does our business need us to do? Well, they need us to

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:06.559
deliver this project that has to do with building some really complex data assets from a bunch of

00:11:06.559 --> 00:11:13.039
different sources, with modeling and deriving some new attributes in that data, with working

00:11:13.039 --> 00:11:20.400
up a method for sort of making that data available to consumers through an API or through a platform

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:25.919
or whatever. That's what the business needs. That's why we have a job. And I know that's

00:11:25.919 --> 00:11:31.760
supposed to be the thing that is like motivating is create shareholder value. But the thing that

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:38.479
as a leader, you get to do when you've got a team who understands those expectations is we get to,

00:11:38.479 --> 00:11:43.119
I get to spend a lot of time talking with the folks on my team about, okay, how do we get to

00:11:43.119 --> 00:11:49.599
what it is that you want to make? This is where we get freedom. And in my organization, we've got a

00:11:49.599 --> 00:11:55.440
really explicit process, this annual cycle of goal setting where, you know, you put out the big rocks

00:11:55.440 --> 00:12:00.239
each year. This year, we've got to rebuild this great big complex thing. We've got to come up with

00:12:00.239 --> 00:12:05.359
a market model. We've got to do some supply chain stuff. You put all those things, you know, that's

00:12:05.359 --> 00:12:11.520
your portfolio of work. We pair each of those things with a question about, okay, how do you

00:12:11.520 --> 00:12:19.039
want to grow while you do the work this year? And that seed of conversation lets us really dig into

00:12:19.679 --> 00:12:24.239
person by person on the team, what are the skills that you want to develop while we do the work

00:12:25.119 --> 00:12:29.919
that we know that we've got to deliver this year? As a team, we have strategic goals for

00:12:29.919 --> 00:12:36.320
doing more code-based development, for modernizing some infrastructure, for developing some improved

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:42.640
methods of communicating with data. And so we can take those team-level goals and we can wrap those

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:48.479
into individual goals for every person, for every one of the what's. So it's, I want to write more

00:12:48.479 --> 00:12:54.320
Python. I want to get more into Git for collaborative version control with my team,

00:12:54.320 --> 00:13:00.880
right? These are the kinds of things that as you get to practice them, I think you get to sort of

00:13:01.440 --> 00:13:07.359
instantiate in your work, the day-to-day sense of I'm doing data science the way that I see it

00:13:07.359 --> 00:13:15.200
practiced. Even if you're not like fitting models every day, right? You're doing valuable work and

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:19.200
you're getting to do it in a way that is rewarding and that is skill building. And the

00:13:19.200 --> 00:13:26.400
critical thing here is that as a team, we've aligned on the goal, the requirement that as we

00:13:26.400 --> 00:13:32.400
meet our business needs, we're also going to develop as people. And that's a real responsibility

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:40.159
for me to be checking in with as we go throughout the year. Okay. So we've set up these goals for

00:13:40.159 --> 00:13:45.359
people to develop themselves, to grow skills throughout the year, as we meet our business

00:13:45.359 --> 00:13:55.200
needs. But there's danger in believing that like that's it. And so as a leader, the next things

00:13:55.200 --> 00:14:00.320
that I have to do is make sure, sort of have to gut check, have to check against some instincts

00:14:00.320 --> 00:14:05.359
that I think start to surface as you say, okay, I'm going to lead a pragmatic data team. We're

00:14:05.359 --> 00:14:12.880
going to do what the business needs us to do so that we can fulfill these roles. There's an

00:14:12.880 --> 00:14:16.880
instinct that you find yourself in to say yes to everything. Got to push back against that.

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:22.880
Being pragmatic doesn't mean that you just do everything that the business needs. Ideally,

00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:26.640
you're growing in credibility so that you can push back on the things that don't really make

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:30.960
sense, right? You need to become a stakeholder. You need to be at the table with the business to

00:14:30.960 --> 00:14:36.479
push back. So we don't say yes to everything. It also really importantly, it doesn't mean that the

00:14:36.479 --> 00:14:43.039
folks on your team are somehow sublimating their ambitions around data science into this channel

00:14:43.039 --> 00:14:48.880
that you've got. And if you get a sense that people are feeling that way, you've got to pivot.

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:58.400
You've got to steer so that you can avoid that cycle because of the sense of like, well,

00:14:59.359 --> 00:15:02.479
this leads you to the kind of situation where people think they're putting in their time.

00:15:02.479 --> 00:15:06.159
We don't want people to feel like they're putting in their time. If we're doing this goal setting

00:15:06.159 --> 00:15:11.840
well, it shouldn't feel that way. But we've got to watch for the sense of like, you know,

00:15:12.719 --> 00:15:18.000
I'm throwing myself on the grenade for the greater good. Like that doesn't serve anybody.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:22.479
There's also a risk when you're being pragmatic of the sense of like, we're going to build a thing

00:15:22.479 --> 00:15:26.719
and we're going to own it forever. There's a trade-off here that's worth considering.

00:15:26.719 --> 00:15:32.080
If we build a thing using the tools available to us or using the capabilities that we want to

00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:37.280
stretch into, maybe we own some infrastructure for a while, but we got to learn a bunch along

00:15:37.280 --> 00:15:42.400
the way. Sometimes that's a really good trade-off. Sometimes that really lets the team get into a new

00:15:42.400 --> 00:15:47.520
space, make something effective, and then iterate from there to like, what is the next sort of

00:15:48.640 --> 00:15:54.080
level of sophistication in that? But it's worth, again, asking that question. If we build this

00:15:54.080 --> 00:15:58.880
and it works, are they going to keep wanting it from us? And if so, are we going to be ready

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:03.359
to keep providing it? That's one of those checkpoints that we have to check in with

00:16:03.359 --> 00:16:07.280
ourselves to make sure that we've got, at least that we've thought about that, that we've thought

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:18.080
about that potential risk. So take a sword. Okay. So we're doing good planning. We're meeting

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:23.599
business needs and hopefully people feel like they're getting to develop their skills as we go.

00:16:23.679 --> 00:16:28.159
This creates, I think, another kind of virtuous cycle. And the one thing I haven't talked about

00:16:28.159 --> 00:16:34.559
yet is broader visibility. Here's the thing that I wish I'd done like two years ago,

00:16:34.559 --> 00:16:39.599
which is create a forum, a regular event where the folks on my team basically get to be on a stage.

00:16:40.320 --> 00:16:45.280
What we found in the past seven or eight months since starting a monthly event where my team just,

00:16:45.919 --> 00:16:48.799
we just get together in front of an audience and talk about what we're doing,

00:16:49.520 --> 00:16:53.760
is it creates a community. It creates this platform where they get to talk about what

00:16:53.760 --> 00:17:00.159
they're excited about, what they're learning, the ways in which they've solved particular problems.

00:17:00.159 --> 00:17:06.079
And the response from our kind of community of stakeholders is so encouraging and so

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:11.839
that it's really, really gratifying. And it's really, really fun as a leader

00:17:11.839 --> 00:17:16.880
to see the members of your team sort of getting up, showing off what they're doing and getting

00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:24.800
that reinforcement cycle from the folks they work with. And that culminates in the sense of,

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:29.839
hey, we're developing, we're getting better, we're earning the opportunity to stake out more

00:17:29.839 --> 00:17:33.359
of our own path. We're getting more and more credible, more and more successful.

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:42.239
Okay. So we've got our gear, we've got our tools. We've gone from this sense of how do we get to the

00:17:42.239 --> 00:17:50.079
mountain to at least feeling supported, I hope, in knowing that we're working towards a shared

00:17:50.079 --> 00:17:55.760
goals. And that along the way, we're developing the skills that really feel rewarding and

00:17:55.760 --> 00:18:00.239
gratifying in doing the work that we do. As a leader, if we're doing that well,

00:18:01.119 --> 00:18:06.640
then I think we're doing okay for the folks on our team. And as data scientists,

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:10.880
if we can get into a team like that and feel successful and feel like we're growing,

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:18.319
then I think we ought to keep doing that. So that's what I got. Thank you. Appreciate

00:18:18.319 --> 00:18:20.479
this session. Appreciate everybody. Here's how to find me.

00:18:27.199 --> 00:18:31.040
All right. Thank you. So we have a couple of questions all queued up.

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:36.560
Do you have any tips on avoiding burnout from consistently putting out fires,

00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:40.239
completing ad hoc requests, in addition to managing your main projects?

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:50.239
Yeah, it's really hard. I think if folks have a sense that all they're doing is putting out fires,

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:56.959
one thing to do is to try to share that work more. So try to introduce a way to be collaborative

00:18:56.959 --> 00:19:01.760
so that you don't just have a single point of contact who's the only person who can respond

00:19:01.760 --> 00:19:06.719
to those sorts of things. That sometimes requires some growth in a team. And so if you can make a

00:19:07.680 --> 00:19:12.800
value case to have help, then I think that that can help with that sort of situation.

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:19.359
But it's tough. We don't want people to feel like their job is just taking tickets.

00:19:21.040 --> 00:19:28.239
And so that's challenging for sure. All right. Where do you draw the line between

00:19:28.239 --> 00:19:36.160
data scientists and data analysts? I think that's part of the dilemma. I think that there's a lot

00:19:36.160 --> 00:19:43.760
of overlap. In some places, it's who's your audience. In some places, the audience for

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:53.760
the data scientists are the analysts. In other places, there's a whole lot of overlap. In our

00:19:53.760 --> 00:20:01.119
organization, analysts are the folks who sit with their businesses, whereas we sit in a central

00:20:01.119 --> 00:20:04.959
function. So that's one way to do that differentiation. The value payoff of what

00:20:04.959 --> 00:20:09.520
you do, though, I think there's a ton of overlap. And I think that's okay.

